<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1913-03-30T14:36:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1913-03-30T14:36:00-05:00" n="951" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d951">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/6944.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Ambassador</gloss> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegrams—Paraphrases.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Mexico</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1913-03-30T13:00:00-06:36">
                                    <hi rend="italic">March 30, 1913—1 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>145. The necessity for an immediate meeting for the consideration of
                            recognition and of general claims is urged on me by my diplomatic
                            colleagues, but as I have no instructions as to recognition I declined
                            to call a meeting at the Embassy and said I would participate in one at
                            the British Legation. Please send instruction at once.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Henry Lane Wilson</hi>.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>